VIRAL GASTROENTERITIS UPDATE 2002 - UK & IRELAND (05)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[The outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis included in these updates have the
characteristics of "winter vomiting disease", and are presumed to be caused
by Norwalk-like viruses (i.e., caliciviruses classified in the genus
_Norovirus_), although this is rarely confirmed microbiologically. The UK
and Ireland seem to be particularly prone at present to outbreaks of
"winter-vomiting" disease in institutional settings. - Mod.CP]
In these updates:
[1] Australia
[2] Scotland (Edinburgh Hospital)
[3] Scotland (Hospitals in Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Central Belt)
[4] England (Blackpool Hotel)
******
[1]
Date: Sun 17 Nov 2002
From: Robyn Donnellan <DonnellanR2@sesahs.nsw.GOV.AU>

Australian Experience
---------------------
Earlier this year in Randwick (a suburb of Sydney, Australia ) some members
of the community, hospitals, and nursing homes in the surrounding areas
experienced a viral gastroenteritis diagnosed at my hospital as human
calicivirus type 2. Many people were affected by this infectious illness.
Symptoms included lower abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhoea, and or nausea.
At 2 of the teaching hospitals infection control strategies included the
mandatory use of a high filtration respiratory masks when caring for
infected cases (the mask is normally used when caring for patients with
tuberculosis), infected staff remained away from work until 48 hours after
the resolution of symptoms, isolation for 48 hours after the resolution of
symptoms of all infected patient cases, and those exposed to the illness
were cohorted or isolated for 72 hours.
At both teaching hospitals we were able to remain open and accept elective
admissions. The attack rate in staff was high when staff were exposed to the
aerosolised vomitus/ fomites of infected patients or the patients were
immunosuppressed. The immuno-suppressed patients excreted for long periods.
A high level of cleaning and disinfection was necessary. We paid particular
attention to the bathrooms (patient and staff and community) and full
personal protective equipment PPE was used by the cleaning staff (including
a high filtration mask).
--
Robyn Donnellan
CNC Infection Surveillance
Prince of Wales & Sydney Children's Hospital
Randwick NSW Australia.
<DonnellanR2@sesahs.nsw.GOV.AU>
